      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown and build",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a wide pan over high heat. Fry the {{onion}}, {{carrot}}, and {{celery}} for 5 minutes. Add the {{garlic}} and {{tomato-puree}} and cook for 1 minute. Add the {{beef-mince}} and break it up thoroughly, cooking until browned all over with no pink remaining. Pour in the {{red-wine}} and let it bubble for 1 minute. Tip everything into the slow cooker. Add the {{tinned-tomatoes}}, {{stock-beef}}, {{bay-leaves}}, {{oregano-dried}}, {{sea-salt-fine}}, and {{black-pepper}}. Stir to combine. Cook on low for 6 to 8 hours. Remove the {{bay-leaves}}, taste and adjust seasoning. The sauce should be thick and deeply coloured.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Remove the lid and cook on high for the last 30 minutes to reduce. For a thicker result from the start, omit the stock entirely",
              "cause": "Too much liquid or lid not sealing properly",
              "symptom": "Sauce watery after 6 hours"
            },
            {
              "fix": "The mince must be broken into small pieces in the pan before adding to the slow cooker, large clumps will not break down further in wet heat",
              "cause": "Not broken up thoroughly before slow cooking",
              "symptom": "Mince in clumps rather than broken into the sauce"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Always taste and season after the cook. The long reduction concentrates salt, taste before adding more. A small splash of red wine vinegar can also lift a flat sauce",
              "cause": "Seasoning not adjusted at the end",
              "symptom": "Sauce tastes flat despite the long cook"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Slow-cooker bolognese is a batch-cook staple. Start it in the morning and have pasta ready for dinner with no further effort. It freezes in portions and tastes better reheated the next day. Use any leftovers for lasagne, the sauce is already the right consistency to layer.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
